Dayo Ojerinde Mrs Oluwabunmi Amao has assumed office as the new Director-General of the Centre for Black and African Arts and Civilisation. A statement from the Special Assistant to the President (Media), Office of the Minister of Information and Culture, Segun Adeyemi, said Amao’s appointment took effect from August 26. She took over from Mrs Osaro Osayande who served as the director overseeing the office of the Director-General between December 2019 and August 2020. With the appointment, Amao becomes the sixth substantive director-general of the Centre for Black and African Arts and Civilisation, an agency under the Federal Ministry of Information and Culture. The new DG was a Special Adviser on Culture and Tourism as well as a Special Adviser on Establishment and Training under the administration of the Late Abiola Ajimobi in Oyo State between 2011 and 2015. The statement said, “Born in Kano, Mrs Olubunmi Amao is an indigene of Ibadan in Oyo State, Nigeria. Her educational background spanned through United Kingdom and the United States of America, where she obtained B.Sc (business administration and accounting), MBA ( business administration and finance) in 1981 and 1982 respectively. “Upon completion of the mandatory NYSC, she worked as the first Accountant with Joas Group of Companies, where she eventually rose to the post of Group Managing Director of the Companies.” She is a Fellow of the Institute of Tourism Professional and was also a co- founder of the House of Furniture and Designs Limited in Nigeria, the statement added. Copyright PUNCH.
